'''Alinaghi Khamoushi''' ({{lang-fa|علینقی‌ خاموشی|ʿAli-Naqi Ḵāmuši}}) is an Iranian [[business magnate]] and [[Iranian Principlists|conservative]] politician.

An influential [[Lobbying|lobbyist]] in Iranian political and economic arena, he is a senior member of the [[Islamic Coalition Party]] and runs three large textile companies owned by two religious centers and the CEO of Iran Investments Company.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tehranbureau/2011/02/the-pesudo-parliament-of-irans-private-sector-i.html|title=The Pseudo-Parliament of Iran's Private Sector|date=23 February 2011|access-date=11 June 2017|author=Hamid Farokhnia}}</ref>

Khamoushi served as the president of the [[Iran Chamber of Commerce Industries and Mines]] from 1984 to 2007.<ref name="I">{{cite encyclopedia|title =JAMʿIYAT-E MOʾTALEFA-YE ESLĀMI i. Hayʾathā-ye Moʾtalefa-ye Eslāmi 1963-79|encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]]|date=February 20, 2013|orig-year=December 15, 2008|publisher=Bibliotheca Persica Press|location=New York City|url =http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/jamiyat-e-motalefa-i|volume= XIV|last1= Rahnema|first1=Ali|access-date=March 15, 2016|series=Fasc. 5|pages=483–500|chapter-url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/jamiyat-e-motalefa-ii|chapter=ii. Jamʿiyat-e Moʾtalefa and the Islamic Revolution}}</ref> He also represented [[Tehran, Rey, Shemiranat and Eslamshahr (electoral district)|Tehran, Rey, Shemiranat and Eslamshahr electoral district]] in the [[Parliament of Iran]] from 1992 to 1996.<ref name="I"/> Khamoushi was the first head of [[Mostazafan Foundation]], a [[Bonyad]].<ref name="I"/>

