{{Infobox NRHP | name =Standard Oil Building | nrhp_type = | image = Baltimore Standard Oil Bldg.JPG | caption = Standard Oil Building, March 2012 | location= 501 St. Paul St., [[Baltimore, Maryland]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|17|43|N|76|36|49|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA | built = {{Start date|1922}} | architect = Friz, Clyde N. | architecture = Beaux Arts | added = December 1, 2000 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 00001461<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} '''Standard Oil Building''', also known as the Stanbalt Building, is a historic [[office building]] located at [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]]. It is a 15-story [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux Arts]] [[skyscraper]] designed by [[Clyde N. Friz]] (1867-1942), one of Baltimore's best-known Beaux Arts designers, and built in 1922. The steel-frame "U"-shaped office building is clad in limestone. It was built by the [[Standard Oil Company]] at a time when that business was once one of the nation's principal corporations, the dominant supplier of gasoline and fuels.<ref name="mht_ihp">{{cite web|url=https://mht.maryland.gov/secure/medusa/PDF/NR_PDFs/NR-1255.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Standard Oil Building|date=May 2000|accessdate=2016-03-01 |author=George E. Thomas|publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>
Standard Oil Building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2000.<ref name="nris"/> In its later years as an office building, the building primarily housed offices for the City of Baltimore. Following an extensive, $25 million renovation, the building reopened as residential apartments in 2002 by the [[Southern Management Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2002-10-17/news/0210170346_1_standard-oil-building-mount-vernon-downtown|date=2002-10-17|work=Old Standard Oil Building gets apartment makeover|publisher=Baltimore Sun}}</ref>
