{{Infobox NRHP | name = Thurmond and Lucy Chatham House | nrhp_type = | image = | caption = | location = 112 N. Stratford Rd., [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]] | coordinates = {{coord|36|5|51|N|80|16|36|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = North Carolina#USA | built = {{Start date|1925}} | architect = Keen and Wallace | builder = McNeill Construction Company | architecture = Classical Revival | added = August 18, 2014 | area = {{convert|2.72|acre}} | governing_body = Private | refnum = 14000493<ref name="nps">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20140829.htm|title=National Register of Historic Places Listings|date=2014-08-29|work=Weekly List of Actions Taken on Properties: 8/18/14 through 8/23/14|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> }} The '''Thurmond and Lucy Chatham House''' is a historic home located at [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], [[Forsyth County, North Carolina]]. It was built in 1925, and is a [[Neoclassical architecture|Classical Revival]] style [[stucco]]ed dwelling consisting of a 2 1/2-story main block flanked by two-bay-wide projecting hip-roofed sections. It has a tall hip roof and bluestone terrace that fills the rear courtyard of the "H"-shaped plan. The house encompasses 9,065-square-feet of living space. Also on the property is a contributing 1 1/2-story garage / apartment. It was built for Congressman and businessman [[Richard Thurmond Chatham]] (1896–1957), who also served as president of the [[Chatham Manufacturing Company]] and his wife, Lucy Hodgin Hanes.<ref name=nrhpinv>{{Cite web |author= Heather Fearnbach|title=Thurmond and Lucy Chatham House |work=National Register of Historic Places - Nomination and Inventory |date=March 2014|url=http://www.hpo.ncdcr.gov/nr/FY1051.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=North Carolina State Historic Preservation Office |accessdate=2014-11-01}}</ref>
It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2014.<ref name=nps />
